Every part of your present conduct agrees with the rest, and I am truly amazed at the blindness which fear, faction, and office have created! This war not felt by the poor? When was there a war in which its miseries and its burthens were not supported by them? When was there a war, of two years, so oppressive and teeming with misery as the present? Under the most favourable circumstances, what is the condition of the poor? You are a statesman; do you not know? I will not suppose you are to be taught that the tillage of the land, and the labour bestowed upon its products, constitute the whole wealth of men. Who are the tillers? Who are the manufacturers? The poor. Without their labour, the earth itself would be barren. The foundation of the laws of property is that each man is affirmed to be entitled to the produce of his own industry. If these original laws therefore were executed, with all the rigour with which it is pretended they ought to be observed, the poor and the poor only would be entitled to eat; for it is their labour alone that produces food. For this labour, what do the rich give them in return? Oppression, insult, contempt. Of the only thing which could conduce to their happiness, knowledge, they are debarred;


by the continual drudgery to which they are subjected. Examine for a moment the relative situation, between them and their taskmasters. Who make the laws? The rich‚ÄîWho alone can with probable impunity break the laws?‚ÄîThe rich‚ÄîWho are impelled by want and misery to break them, and afterward are imprisoned, transported, and hanged?‚ÄîThe poor.‚ÄîWho do the work?‚ÄîThe poor.‚ÄîWho reap the fruits?‚ÄîThe rich.‚ÄîWho pay the taxes?‚ÄîThe poor; for their labours pay every thing.‚ÄîWho impose the taxes?‚ÄîThe rich, whose luxury devours what the labours of the poor produce.‚ÄîOn what do the rich feed?‚ÄîOn the product of the poor's misery.‚ÄîOn what do the rich ride?‚ÄîOn the bent and half-broken back of the poor.‚ÄîWhat supports the fine houses, parks, and palaces, of the rich?‚ÄîThe hunger and thirst of the poor.‚ÄîWith what do they purchase their gaudy carriages; fit only to engender disease and indolence; in which they loll, look down on and drive over the industrious man on foot?‚ÄîWith the price of wretchedness, paid by the poor.‚ÄîOn what do the rich revel and riot, make feasts, and routes, and encourage gaming, gluttony, drunkenness, and every species of vice?‚ÄîOn the groans and tears and sweat and blood of the poor.‚ÄîFor what do the rich quarrel?‚ÄîFor the groans and tears and sweat


and blood of the poor.‚ÄîHave not the rich clubs, night meetings, and societies?‚ÄîThe rich have public brothels; where they are guilty of practices such as none but appetites the most detestable and depraved could endure. They have gaming-houses; where they have frequently been known to stake the day's labour of half a million of men on a single card, or dice: and they have clubs, in which politicians meet; to consult how they may trick one another, buy rotten boroughs, and secure to themselves the fruit of the labour which they lay on the shoulders of the poor.‚ÄîAnd do no justices, no constables, no lord mayors, interfere?‚ÄîNo: they say what they please, do what they please, and publish what they please against each other, and provided they do not attack the craft, on which they all fatten‚ÄîWhy are the rich proud, and arrogant, and insolent?‚ÄîBecause the poor are ignorant, and distressed, and heartbroken.‚ÄîWhy do the rich treat the poor with contempt?‚ÄîBecause the poor must either bend or starve.‚ÄîWhy are the rich tyrants?‚ÄîBecause the poor are humbled, and terrified till they dare not speak.
